</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="75" pageNumber="76" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1436,151,213]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,151,176]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Distribution.</emphasis>
A fairly frequently encountered species of southern 
<collectingCountry box="[981,1060,152,175]" name="France" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">France</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1076,1127,151,176]" name="Italy" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Italy</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1191,1255,151,176]" name="Spain" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Spain</collectingCountry>
(reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,246,188,213]" name="Portugal" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Portugal</collectingCountry>
under the name 
<taxonomicName box="[432,535,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Usia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrata">
<emphasis box="[432,535,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">U. atrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and these will almost certainly prove to be correct).
</paragraph>
